<TITLE> Lakhs face floodwaters in NE, central districts </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 2 (bdnews24.com)  Hundreds of thousands have been driven from their homes as rivers overflowed in northeastern and central districts of the country. Almost one lakh people have been beseiged by floodwaters in Kurigram alone, a district relief officer told bdnews24.com. The Flood Forecast and Warning Centre said the Padma and Meghna continued rising Tuesday, while the Brahmaputra-Jamuna registered a fall at upstream points but continued rising at downstream points. The confluence of the Meghna and Padma will continue rising at a moderate rate for the next 2-3 days, the FFWC said, while low lying areas in the districts of Serajganj, Tangail, Munshiganj, Manikganj, Faridpur, Madaripur, Shariatpur, Dohar and Nawabganj of Dhaka district, Shibganj and Sadar of Chapainawabganj district is likely to flood further over the next 24-48 hours. In Kurigram, district relief officer Tofazzal Hossain told bdnews24.com about 90,000 people of 30,729 families have been affected as 425 villages in 56 unions of the districts were inundated. About 23,000 houses have been damaged. About 750 square kilometres in 56 unions has been flooded. The relief officer said crops on about 41,118 hectares of land have gone under flood water, while some 232 kilometres of mud roads, 7 kilometres of metalled road and 8 kilometres of embankments were damaged. Though waters of the Dharla, Brahmaputra and Teesta marked a fall, the flood situation has not improved in the district. Water Development Board engineer Zafar Ali said the Dharla receded by 10 cm in last 24 hours but was still flowing 25 cm above the danger mark. In Sherpur, the Sadar upazila has witnessed flash floods. Flood water is running over points of the Sherpur-Jamalpur highway. Low lying areas have been inundated as waters of the Old Brahmaputra continued to rise, swelling by 16 cm in the last 24 hours but not yet crossing the danger mark. Aman paddy, seedbeds and vegetable farms on a vast tract of Sherpur went under floodwater. The flood situation in Faridpur also worsened as the water level of the Padma continued to rise. The Padma swelled by 9 cm and was flowing 85 cm above the red mark at Gualundo point. New areas are being flooded. Faridpur Sadar upazila nirbahi officer Md Mahbubur Rahman Faruki said tens of thousands of at least three unions have been marooned. He said distribution of rice on a limited scale among the victims would start from Wednesday. In Chapainawabganj, flood water has submerged 2,425 hectares of land in the Sadar and Shibganj upazilas, district relief and rehabilitation officer Nazrul Islam said. Waters of the Padma and the Mahananda continue to swell, with the Padma flowing 57 centimetres above the danger mark. The flood situation in Manikganj continued to deteriorate as the Jamuna steadily swelled, with at least 30 unions being flooded. bdnews2
